Five passivated implanted silicon detectors
were installed in the scattering chamber at the angles
60., 90., 105., 150 degrees with respect to the beam
direction.
Berillium target was oriented with its normal
at 135 degrees to the beam direction.  Another details

The accelerators provided H1+, H2+, H3+ hydrogen
beams.

x4freetext: Noany analysis is presented
The evaporated berillium film thickness was monitored -
during the fabrication - with a quartz oscillator
gauge.
Target thickness was to be 10 microgramm/cm**2.  The
target was deposited on cooled copper backing.  A
liquid-nitrogen cooled copper shroud was installed near
the target holder to minimie carbon deposition on the
target.

x4freetext: MONTE CARLO simulating
code.
- By authors.  The MONTE CARLO simulating program
included:
1. The setup geometry,
2. The spot sie of the ion beam at the target,
3. The energy loss and the energy straggling of the
projectiles and ejectiles in the target, in the foils
covering the detectors, and in the dead layer of the
detectors,
4. The kinematics of the ejectiles,
5. The intrinsic energy resolution of the detectors
the simulated spectra were fitted to measured spectra
with well-resolved peaks of the ejectiles;  this
fitting allowed to determine the energy calibration of
the spectra, the thickness of the foils and of the dead
layers, and the intrinsic energy resolution of the
detectors.
The result is presented in data table two times.

x4freetext: See sample
The target together with the chamber and the
detector holders formed the faraday cup
Four passived inplanted silicon detectors were
placed at 130 degrees around of beam axis and at a
distance of 42 millimeters.
The precision of beam current measurements.
The uncertainty for absolute solid angle.
The uncertainty of detection angle.
The uncertainty of target composition.
The uncertainty of stopping power.
Errors qouted arise from uncertainties in the
number of counts, incident proton energy, angular
distribution, and target deterioration. All values have
a common additional error of 13% due to uncertainties
in current measurement, absolute solid angle, detection
angle, target composition and stopping power.
Four target were used:
1. 10 microgramm/cm**2. The target was used for 71-330
KeV.
2. 20 microgramm/cm**2. The target was used for 20-100
KeV.
3. 100 microgramm/cm**2. The target was used for 18,20
KeV
4. 100 microgramm/cm**2. The target was used for 16 KeV
the thicknesses obtained from quartz oscillator gauge
during target fabrication.
Target #1 and #2 were bombarded at higher energies with
relatively low proton dose. For the targets, the
observed reaction yields at the reference energies
stayed constant in time within 3%.
Targets #3 and #4 were used in the lowest energies and
bombarded each with 100 coulomb accumulated charge.
Linear relationship between yield and accumulated
charge. The targets stability was tested every 2 hours
of running time via the reaction yield at 60 KeV.
Needed corrections for thickness target changing and
energy shift due to carbon deposition were applied.
The number of used target.
The energy of used accelerator.
The mass - in atomic mass unit - of one charged
hydrogen ion of beam.
